segments.text: was being involved.
And then know ahead of time what was going on.
And if I didn't like it, do all I could to head it off.
It's easier to prevent something than it is to change it.
More after it's done, yeah.
Yeah.
And so I was a director for about 10 years.
And one day, some of them came up to me and said, would you run for chairman of the board?
And I said, yeah, I would like to.
And this was in...
That's when they first approached me, because it was in 78, February of 78, I was elected chairman of the board.
And that whole year I was... Is that rotating, or is that an annual, or can you continue re-election?
In the TVMA, you cannot be re-elected to the post that you have.
That's in any of the posts.
If you're third vice president, you cannot run for third vice president.
Now, if you're second vice president, you can run for third vice president.
But you cannot run for the office that you presently hold.
So I finished the year as chairman of the board, and I ran for third vice president, and I got beat.

I got beat out by Dennis McIntosh, who had gotten beat out twice, but he had run for third vice president, got beat out, and he ran again for second vice president, got beat out by the same guy, and then the next year came up, I was running for third vice president, so he ran for third vice president, and he beat me.
So I was as stubborn as he was, so I ran against him, ran for second vice president the next year, and he beat me again.
And in the meantime I got busy and I didn't have enough time to deal with it.
So I laid out several years, I mean I was still a director, but I wasn't running for any of the offices.
And I guess it was in the, I'm not sure just what year it was, was it eight years ago?
I guess it was in eight.
I was just 15 years old at that time, so it was in 82.
Maybe that's when we just changed over to the new bylaws, which had a chairman-elect.
So they no longer, this is the last time they would elect a chairman because there's one elected chairman-elect, and it was in the early years.
And I was sitting out there waiting for the board of directors meeting to start, and there's four or five of them come over to me, and they says...
will you run for chairman of the board?
What?
And we want you to run for chairman of the board.
We've got somebody we want to get in as chairman-elect.
He says, but you've already been chairman once, so you know about what it is.
You don't need to be chairman-elect.
Will you run for chairman-elect?
I said, sure.
And so at the end of the meeting, when they come up, I'm in for chairman-elect.
I'm in chairman, and I won.
So as far as I know, I was the first one to ever be, first and only one to ever be chairman of the board twice.
But there was a stand in between.
And I succeeded and went up the steps, third vice president, second vice president, first president, second president, all through it.
I had been opposed on several of those, but I was fortunate all of those I did win.
So you became president in 87.
Now, at that time, were there any special problems or situations sort of facing the association that you felt like you were particularly willing to deal with?
Well, the biggest thing that I was wanting to try to deal with at that time was membership and apathy.
Membership's always going to be a problem.
I feel that there is no reason in the world why we don't have 100% of the veterinarians belong to the state association, but we don't.
We have about two-thirds, which every time I go to one of the other states, they say, well, you're doing real good, but I'm still not proud of that.
So I've worked hard on trying to get increasing membership.
We get some, we get some.
But there's a whole lot of them that the veterinarian today is smarter than they were when I first got in.
There's a whole bunch of them that can figure.
They know that they don't pass laws that are good for veterinarians that are members of the association.
They pass laws that are good for veterinarians.
being that we've got an association that's strong, and they work and lobby and get these things paid for.
They're willing to let you do it.
And so for the $150 that they paid, you know how many cases of beer they can buy?
I mean, you know, figure that real quick.
I mean, shoot, I can ride along free.
And like I've told them, you know, the apathy fits in there then, too.
We've got a lot of members that are paying in.
to do things for other people.
And they don't ever say anything to them.
Where if the same guy was running the wire over their house and draining their electricity from them, so he didn't have to pay the electric bill, man, they'd jump on him in a hurry.
If he was out there siphoning gas out of his truck, he'd be on him in a hurry.
But it's the same thing, see.
And say, well, he's a good old boy.
I know him.
And you know that my kids go to school with his kids and all that.
I don't ever say anything to him.
It's stealing.
Somewhat in the same connection, what kind of relationships did you have with the college when you were president?
And do you see an apathy or a schism or a lack of communication between the college and the profession?
Well, the college in general, I have good relationships with.
Individuals at the college, it all depends.
Some of them I have very bad relations with.
I've never been one to beat around the bush.
I call a spade a spade, a son of a bitch a son of a bitch, and that's the way it is.
And some of them don't like it.
And the college is, I see it, and you may take offense to admit that you're part of the college, but the college, in a way, is only interested about the college.
Yeah, I think there is.
They're looking after themselves.
They claim, well, it's for the profession.
And yes, it is, in a way.
But yet, they're still, number one, it's a self-aggrandizing sort of thing.
I mean, they're not going to beat themselves out of a job.
And it's always looking, well, can I get another brother in here?
Like I was mentioning, the difference in the size of the faculty.
Yeah, I picked up on that.
19 when I was there, they've got twice as many students now, and they've got five or six times more faculty, and they're short-handed.
Some of them are not working.
And I'm not sure just where a nice, happy medium is there.
I mean, I don't want to be one that is against progress.
But I don't want to be just, you know, you're paying the bills for all kinds of things.
So there are some at the college that, I mean, in general, I got along good.
Oh, yeah, I know.
I mean, I went out of my way, for one thing, because in the position as president of the TVMA, you need to keep good relations.
And we even established an extra committee the year that I was president-elect for coordinating a lot of things to where we get a little better relationship.
Because one of the bad relationships we had with it, I was telling you, we don't have but about two-thirds
membership in the total profession in there, but it's even lower than that of college professors.
Yeah, that's what I've picked up on quite a bit.
And there again, when I go to other states that have universities, they say, God, you're doing real good.
There's only one state that has a better percentage.
That's North Carolina, and the state pays their dues.
So they all belong.
Well, when they established their veterinary school there, they established it that the fees that they take in, part of it goes into a fund to pay the professors professional dues to various things.
And a certain percentage of that goes in that pot for that.
And they're the only ones that are ahead of us.
But that's kind of a problem area, I sense.
And you need to be heading back to your office pretty quick.
But what are some of the
What do you see as the major problems facing the profession today?
And if you were writing a history of veterinary medicine, what kind of message do you think such a history should convey?
The history is there for itself.
The future bothers me in a way, except that I'm an eternal optimist.
I think veterinarians are hardy and they're going to survive.
Things are going to go now.
Veterinarians need to quit being so apathetic

And I have to say veterinarians and Aggies, because there's so many of them, and most of the veterinarians in the state are Aggies, and they're all gung-ho for their school, and anything the school does has got to be right, you know.
It's not subtle.
They've got to question a few things that come by.
I used to be the same way, you know.
Sure, yeah.
Whatever the school did, you know, that is right, because these guys are the professors.
They're the ones that taught me.
I didn't start thinking different until none of those that taught me are there anymore.
Is the Aggie Association a professional plus?
I don't know.
I never thought about that before.
I don't know.
With the public, with the general public.
It is and it isn't.
To other Aggies, it darn sure isn't.
Oh, sure.
Others are not because I personally have always said that the two most obnoxious people in the world
As far as school people are concerned are people from Arkansas and people from A&M and outsiders.
And of course if you're an insider, well they're great.
But anyway they tend to never question anything that the school does because it is the school.
The same way for years I'd go to a seminar and because the guy was behind the microphone
Whatever he said was law.
He was right.
That's wrong.
I began to question things.
I'm not the smartest guy in the world, but I'm no dummy.
Some of these things are wrong.
You do need to question.
I think that one of the things that has come up that bothers me more than anything is the fact that
I hate to see anybody give up privileges or things, and they're pushing to get a national license.
I could argue both sides, but I hate to see a state give up its right to issue licenses.
Is the AVMA pushing that role?
Oh, yeah.
Everybody's pushing to get, you know, if you can be licensed in the country, then you can go anywhere you want.
I'm not for that, and also special licenses.
I agree with that.
to a point, depending on what it is.
But if they're going to start training technicians to do things, you're going to do it in the way of veterinarians.
And the first thing, it's going to come to a mechanic.
It's no longer going to be an art of medicine.
It's going to be a mechanic of medicine.
And it worries me.
I'm not going to live that long.
I was watching that, then, because I was not aware of that national licensing.
Well, they're pushing for it.
Pew Report is just out in there.
I got it.
I've been going through that.
I'm reading it.

There are some things in there that, there again, I can see both sides, and I can argue both ways, and it's like so many things that you have to be careful what you allow, because when you allow these, you open the gate for the other.
You cannot be selective.
So if you can't, you better shut the door on the thing that you like.
I'd like to see...
limited licensure.
Just telling you, my youngest daughter is not a veterinarian, but she's a breeding specialist.
And she does have real transfer.
Well, this is a big hot thing right now.
And they had proposed last legislation to allow them at your licensing for real transfer, those that were not veterinarians.
Well, they decided, no, it's what we'll do.
We'll leave it like it is.
And as long as nobody is complaining, it's OK.
But I feel that it should be limiting licensure.
Now, I feel this way that if you have somebody that's a specialist, I mean, she's got her master's in that field.
It's not a matter of you're taking some guy that's a dropout from high school, and you're training him to do this and letting him do it.
I mean, there's a difference there.
There's a difference in degree and difference in skill.
Well, this would, to me, be something like your anesthesiologist or something like that.
Well, this is where limited licensure should come.
See, there's a lot of people that are board-certified specialists that would like to move to this state, but say their surgeries are filled.
They have to take the general testing.
Hey, now wait a minute, why don't you license me to do surgery on a referral basis?
I can see that that could probably and should be done.
But they do that for the professors, more or less.
They have a limited licensure for the professors at the college.
For a long time, they didn't have to have a license if they were in the college.
Well, now it's in the law.
They have to have one, but they can take a separate kind of an exam, but they have to only work
They can do consulting work.
I mean, they can't moonlight.
They can just do what comes through the clinic.
And there's some of them before, you know, they're doing the clinic, and then they got a friend out here, you know, they do this, and they moonlight.
Well, that's illegal because it's their licenses they're not taking.
That's interesting.
I can see where that would be.
I mean, none of this is cut and dry that this is good or bad.
With any good, there's always some bad.
Yeah.
So there's really a lot going on in the profession in terms of that.
And that's why I'd
try to stay, I want to be one of those that is in on the discussion.
And at least I know that I got it in my legs even if I got outvoted.
And Lord knows I've been outvoted many, many times.
It's easy.
Well, for one thing, I get uneasy if things are going to railroad.
I mean, everything is all good.
Now, I'll stand up and I'll say, I'll holler, hey, now wait a minute.
There's got to be a downside somewhere.
And we better discuss this now and find out what it is ahead of time.
And so I've taken some stands on things that I really didn't believe in.
But just in order to raise the point.
Yeah, and of course then they said, well, Zeke will argue about anything.
They're right.
They're right.
That's good.
That's good.
So you need a good critic around.
Somebody to call the halt to things
I guess I better let you get back to your place of business, but I really appreciate it.
Is there anything that you'd like to know?
Not that I know of right now, but if you don't mind, I'd like to feel free to call.
Anytime.
Let me get your phone number and everything down.
That's the office.
At home, it's 281-8056.
I really don't expect you to call me, but there might be something coming up that I really need some good information on.
